{"_id":"jacNePVUVpf5hrvz","name":"Player Character Creation","content":"<h1 dir=\"ltr\">Character Concept</h1>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The first step in making a Volition character is to think about who they are as a person. Eventually, you will be choosing skills and calculating health dice but these qualities are imperfect representations of a realistic character. Deciding the qualities in this section will give you a good idea of who that character is, and then you can decide levels and skills based off of your answers here.</p>\n<h2>Identity</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Your identity is a quick, one-sentence summary of your PC. It should be interesting, unique, and descriptive.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Examples: Rage-fueled samurai avenger, magical historian who studies both the past and future, jester who teases corrupt nobles, or symbiotic fey spirit that can change into a tree</p>\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">Goal</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Your goal is what you ultimately want to see your PC accomplish by the end of the campaign. It should be specific, tangible, and achievable. Your GM will use this to plan out the adventures that the party will go on.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Examples: Take my brother’s place as head of the household, prevent the apocalypse only I have foreseen, perform the greatest heist of the century, or restore life to the grove that I once lived in</p>\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">Connections</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Your connections are living people with whom your PC has some sort of bond. You must write a name and a brief description of the relationship for each connection. Your GM will use these connections to advance the story of the adventure and tie your PC into the world they are creating. You can have as many connections as you like, but as a minimum, you must have at least one connection with each of these types of character:</p>\n<ul>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Another PC</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A friendly NPC</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An enemy NPC</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Examples: Januz Gibas, a drug dealer who grew up on the streets with me. Marcel Zebro, a former lover who killed my mentor.  Bram Kivrav, a prince who I “kidnapped” so he can enjoy life outside the palace. Qay Piy, an ancient spirit of the forest that is always watching me but whose intentions are unknown.</p>\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">Flaw</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Your flaw will make your PC feel real and make their stories more interesting. It should cause negative consequences for your character and be relevant enough to come up somewhat frequently. Choose one from the list below, and then write a sentence describing how it specifically manifests in your character. If you can’t find a good match for the idea you have, have your GM create one for you. </p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Examples: Angry: My temper, especially in battle, is uncontrollable. Cautious: If I haven’t consulted three books, cast two spells peering into the future, and considered all possible outcomes, it’s not worth doing. Carefree: A good laugh is worth any risk, even a night or two in the prison cell, especially if it’s not me in the prison cell. Fear: Technology frightens me, and those who use it cannot be trusted.</p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\">Complication</h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some flaws include a complication, which you can choose as a complication after a messy result from a roll (see below) or when narratively appropriate.</p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\">Experience</h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some flaws provide a method to gain experience (XP), which is described in detail below. XP earned from flaws can be applied to any skill of your choice, but you must choose when the XP is earned. </p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\">Additional Rules</h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Flaws can also include special rules. They are usually some detrimental effect applied to your character or a condition related to the complication or experience. These rules are to help you roleplay your character and provide mechanical effects from good roleplay, but they are simply part of your character’s complete flaw. Feel free to lean into your flaw or skirt around it as much as you desire, even when the mechanical rules do not specifically apply.</p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\">Overcoming a Flaw</h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sometimes, your character might reach a point in the story where they are no longer burdened by their flaw because they have overcome it.  This happens when your character takes an action that is directly contrary to their flaw.  Someone too trusting might finally catch someone in a lie, a greedy person might turn down material gain for a greater good, or vengeful person might finally accept that vengeance will not bring them true happiness. When both you and the GM agree that your character has overcome their flaw, you gain 1 XP in every skill you have, and then you remove your current flaw and add a new one. </p>\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">Other Details</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The following details are important facts to decide for your PC to round out their character concept. Your GM will provide more details on appropriate options for these choices.</p>\n<ul>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Name</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Species</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Homeland</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Age</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Faith</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Appearance</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Personality</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Profession</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Hobbies</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h1 dir=\"ltr\">Starting Skills</h1>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When you create a PC, they start with six different skills of your choice, two of which start at Level 2, while the rest start at Level 1. It is recommended that you take a good mix of offensive, defensive, social, exploration, and information gathering skills, as all of these will be important. Talk with the other members of your party to make sure you have a wide variety of skills among your characters, but a bit of overlap can promote cooperation and spark friendly competition. Skills and their rules are described in more detail in the next section.</p>\n<h1 dir=\"ltr\">Health, Armor, Supply, Gold</h1>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Unless you have a starting skill that says otherwise, your starting health is 6/d6/d6, your starting Armor is 0, your starting Supply is 4/4, and you start with 5 gold. The usages of these attributes is described below.</p>\n<h1 dir=\"ltr\">Equipment and Additional Objects</h1>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You start with a variety of objects in addition to your supply and gold:</p>\n<ul>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">All equipment needed for starting skills</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two objects of your choice, appropriate to your PC</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A level 0 artifact</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"> First, if any of your starting skills require equipment to use, you start with all of those objects. For example, if you start with the Swordsmanship skill, which requires a bladed weapon, you can start with your choice of a scimitar, shortsword, longsword, greatsword, or any other bladed weapon. In addition to equipment, you start with two objects of your choice that are appropriate to your PC. Check with your GM about which objects are appropriate, as they will have the final say on what objects you can choose. Typically, these are related to your character’s backstory or personality traits, such as the broken blade of your former mentor or a treasure map that you’ve been trying to decipher for years. Finally, choose one Level 0 artifact to start with, or have your GM design one for you that is most appropriate for your character. </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"XiploJ9JSc5wv71U":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.kjKPLKcIN7wJPrh0"}}}
