rt at Level 1. It is recommended that you take a good mix of offensive, defensive, social, exploration, and information gathering skills, as all of these will be important. Talk with the other members of your party to make sure you have a wide variety of skills among your characters, but a bit of overlap can promote cooperation and spark friendly competition. Skills and their rules are described in more detail in the next section.</p>\n<h1 dir=\"ltr\">Health, Armor, Supply, Gold</h1>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Unless you have a starting skill that says otherwise, your starting health is 6/d6/d6, your starting Armor is 0, your starting Supply is 4/4, and you start with 5 gold. The usages of these attributes is described below.</p>\n<h1 dir=\"ltr\">Equipment and Additional Objects</h1>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You start with a variety of objects in addition to your supply and gold:</p>\n<ul>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">All equipment needed for starting skills</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Two objects of your choice, appropriate to your PC</p>\n</li>\n<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A level 0 artifact</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"> First, if any of your starting skills require equipment to use, you start with all of those objects. For example, if you start with the Swordsmanship skill, which requires a bladed weapon, you can start with your choice of a scimitar, shortsword, longsword, greatsword, or any other bladed weapon. In addition to equipment, you start with two objects of your choice that are appropriate to your PC. Check with your GM about which objects are appropriate, as they will have the final say on what objects you can choose. Typically, these are related to your character’s backstory or personality traits, such as the broken blade of your former mentor or a treasure map that you’ve been trying to decipher for years. Finally, choose one Level 0 artifact to start with, or have your GM design one for you that is most appropriate for your character. </p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"XiploJ9JSc5wv71U":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.kjKPLKcIN7wJPrh0"}}}
{"_id":"QNaFu3L5Sxtqd15s","name":"Your Player Character","content":"<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:'Century Gothic',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">As a player, you control a Player Character (PC) who is one of the main characters in the story that you, the GM, and the other players are writing together. Your PC is a unique individual with their own feelings, goals, ideas, and flaws. This section describes different aspects of your PC and how you can use them to influence the story.</span></p>\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;border-bottom:solid #b45f06 1pt;margin-top:18pt;margin-bottom:6pt;padding:0pt 0pt 2pt 0pt\"><span style=\"font-size:16pt;font-family:'Century Gothic',sans-serif;color:#b45f06;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">Your Player Character</span></h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:'Century Gothic',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">There are three rules you must follow when you make decisions for your PC. Also, your PC has an identity, a goal, connections, and a flaw, all of which will help you follow these rules.</span></p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:16pt;margin-bottom:4pt\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:'Century Gothic',sans-serif;color:#bf9000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">Your PC is a unique individual in the setting.</span></h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:'Century Gothic',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">Always keep in mind your PC’s identity. You are not your PC, and they will often make decisions that you yourself would not make, even in the exact same situation. They have lived in the GM’s world for their entire life, and have traditions and knowledge that you do not. However, they are still your PC, and the way their identity and flaw interact with your own personality can be very exciting for everyone in the campaign.</span></p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:16pt;margin-bottom:4pt\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:'Century Gothic',sans-serif;color:#bf9000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">Your PC is a character in the story.</span></h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:'Century Gothic',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">All stories have changes and developments in them. Expect your PC to experience challenges and setbacks of varying difficulty. Use your PC’s flaw to create dramatic tension in the story, even if it is detrimental to the party’s overall objectives. The best stories are those in which a character’s flaw is a hindrance to their goal, but they overcome that flaw and finally accomplish the goal. </span></p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:16pt;margin-bottom:4pt\"><span style=\"font-size:13.999999999999998pt;font-family:'Century Gothic',sans-serif;color:#bf9000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">Your PC is a member of the party.</span></h3>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-30425c0a-7fff-50de-f763-cbb362452ce7\"></span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt;font-family:'Century Gothic',sans-serif;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap\">Your PC’s connections tie them both to the world and to the other players at the table. Use these ties to make your PC feel grounded and realistic, as described above. However, unlike most stories written by a single author or director, Volition involves multiple players as well as the GM contributing to the story. Therefore, it is of utmost importance that you play in a way in which everyone has fun. Every PC in the party has their own goals, but PCs should still support each other in those goals. If at any time your PC’s goal is directly opposed to another PC’s goal, one of you must either change the goal or retire the PC (see Retiring a PC). There can be tension and even conflict between PCs, but you should never attempt to kill another PC or completely deny them the opportunity to accomplish their goal.</span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"XiploJ9JSc5wv71U":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.lSYdoJZO8FHSFZMh"}}}
