<li dir=\"ltr\" aria-level=\"1\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">An enemy NPC</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Examples: Januz Gibas, a drug dealer who grew up on the streets with me. Marcel Zebro, a former lover who killed my mentor.  Bram Kivrav, a prince who I “kidnapped” so he can enjoy life outside the palace. Qay Piy, an ancient spirit of the forest that is always watching me but whose intentions are unknown.</p>\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">Flaw</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Your flaw will make your PC feel real and make their stories more interesting. It should cause negative consequences for your character and be relevant enough to come up somewhat frequently. Choose one from the list below, and then write a sentence describing how it specifically manifests in your character. If you can’t find a good match for the idea you have, have your GM create one for you. </p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Examples: Angry: My temper, especially in battle, is uncontrollable. Cautious: If I haven’t consulted three books, cast two spells peering into the future, and considered all possible outcomes, it’s not worth doing. Carefree: A good laugh is worth any risk, even a night or two in the prison cell, especially if it’s not me in the prison cell. Fear: Technology frightens me, and those who use it cannot be trusted.</p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\">Complication</h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some flaws include a complication, which you can choose as a complication after a messy result from a roll (see below) or when narratively appropriate.</p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\">Experience</h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some flaws provide a method to gain experience (XP), which is described in detail below. XP earned from flaws can be applied to any skill of your choice, but you must choose when the XP is earned. </p>\n<h3 dir=\"ltr\">Additional Rules</h3>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Flaws can also include special rules. They are usually some detrimental effect applied to your character or a condition related to the complication or experience. These rules are to help you roleplay